rlm-pubsub-open

Browse Pub/Sub topics AND subscriptions across one or more GCP
projects via fzf and open the selected resource(s) in the GCP
console. The picker is multi-select: TAB toggles entries and Enter
opens every selected topic/subscription at once.

Projects are read from the environment variable PUBSUB_OPEN_PROJECTS,
which must be set before calling this function:

  export PUBSUB_OPEN_PROJECTS=my-project-prod:my-project-dev

PUBSUB_OPEN_PROJECTS is a colon-separated list of GCP project IDs.

PICKER LAYOUT
  Each entry is rendered as:

    <type>        <project>/<name>

  where <type> is one of:

    topic         a Pub/Sub topic
    pull          a pull subscription
    push          a push subscription (HTTP endpoint)
    bigquery      a BigQuery subscription
    cloudstorage  a Cloud Storage subscription

  Because the type is part of the display line, fuzzy-matching across
  it works as expected — type "bigquery" to filter to BigQuery subs,
  "topic" to filter to topics only, or any substring of the resource
  name to narrow further.

  TAB toggles an entry into the selection; Enter opens all selected
  entries. With nothing toggled, Enter opens just the highlighted
  entry.

CACHING
  The combined topic + subscription list is cached in
  ~/.cache/pubsub-open/ keyed by the sorted project list. On the first
  run the list is fetched from GCP; subsequent runs load instantly
  from the cache.

  The fzf entry "--- REFRESH CACHE (cached <age>) ---" opens a second
  picker that lists the configured projects plus an "*** ALL PROJECTS
  ***" sentinel. TAB toggles selection; Enter confirms. Only the
  chosen projects are re-fetched and their entries are replaced in the
  cache — other projects' entries are preserved. Picking the ALL
  sentinel (alone or alongside others) refreshes everything.

ON SELECTION
  For each selected entry:
  1. Prints the GCP console URL to stdout (topic detail page for
     topics, subscription detail page for subscriptions).
  Then, for the whole selection:
  2. Copies all URLs (newline-separated) to the clipboard in one
     shot (pbcopy on macOS, xclip/xsel on Linux).
  3. Opens every URL in the system browser (a single `open` call on
     macOS, one `xdg-open` per URL on Linux).

  If the "--- REFRESH CACHE ---" entry is among the selections it
  takes priority: the cache is refreshed and any co-selected
  resources are ignored.

PREVIEW PANE
  Powered by ~/bin/pubsub-preview. For topics, shows:

    kind, project_id, name, topic_schema, subscriptions

  For subscriptions, shows:

    kind (with detected delivery type), project_id, name, topic,
    state, ack_deadline, retention, plus type-specific config:
      bigquery     → bq_table, use_topic_schema, write_metadata
      cloudstorage → gcs_bucket, filename_prefix/suffix, format
      push         → push_endpoint, oidc_audience
      pull         → (no extra fields)

  Where relevant the values are OSC 8 hyperlinks to the GCP console
  (topic, subscription, schema, BigQuery table, GCS bucket).

  Hyperlinks rely on OSC 8 terminal support (Ghostty, Kitty, WezTerm,
  iTerm2, etc.) and on fzf >= 0.55 (which passes OSC 8 sequences from
  the preview command through when --ansi is enabled — this function
  passes --ansi). In terminals without OSC 8 the text is still
  readable but not clickable.

  When running inside tmux, hyperlinks pass-through must be enabled:

    set -ga terminal-features "*:hyperlinks"

NOTE ON CREATION DATE
  The preview does NOT show a creation timestamp. Pub/Sub does not
  expose one anywhere in its API: not via `gcloud pubsub topics/
  subscriptions describe` (in any of v1, beta, or alpha), and not via
  Cloud Asset Inventory (which returns `createTime: null` for these
  resource types). The only recoverable source is audit logs
  (`google.pubsub.v1.Publisher.CreateTopic` / `Subscriber.
  CreateSubscription`) — too slow for a preview pane and bounded by
  audit-log retention.

Requires: gcloud (Google Cloud SDK), fzf, jq.
